WEBVTT

00:10.311 --> 00:13.312
(needle down on to record)
(static & record scratching)

00:14.015 --> 00:15.714
(percussive score)

00:38.105 --> 00:40.072
(marching snare drum beat)

00:47.248 --> 00:50.149
- NUNZIATA: Councillor Fletcher,
questions to staff.

00:56.824 --> 00:58.757
- FLETCHER: This is
actually about

00:58.759 --> 01:00.659
the name...

01:07.134 --> 01:08.467
Well, the report's called

01:08.469 --> 01:11.637
"To Facilitate CouncilLor
Office Operations"

01:14.742 --> 01:18.177
I think the word "office",
and you might disagree,

01:18.179 --> 01:20.079
should be clarified.

01:24.318 --> 01:27.352
Perhaps it's a poor
choice of a word.

01:31.392 --> 01:33.325
- But I'm not sure
that I would agree.

01:33.327 --> 01:36.562
- FLETCHER: But what does
"office" mean to you?

01:39.767 --> 01:42.601
- Councillor, I'm not sure
how I'm supposed to answer

01:42.603 --> 01:44.303
that question.

01:52.513 --> 01:54.680
- FLETCHER: Well, there's
been criticisms in the past

01:54.682 --> 01:57.883
of how councillors have spent
their money. It's been said:

01:57.885 --> 02:02.421
"Well, that isn't something
you need to run your 'office'."

02:09.363 --> 02:11.864
The notion of this
being something

02:11.866 --> 02:14.800
to run an 'office'...

02:20.174 --> 02:21.840
versus something

02:21.842 --> 02:24.443
that is a general expense,

02:24.778 --> 02:27.546
hasn't been clearly defined.

02:30.918 --> 02:33.118
Would you agree with that?

02:33.120 --> 02:34.853
- CLAIRE: Wait, is that
your actual question?

02:34.855 --> 02:36.221
What a line item
should be called?

02:36.223 --> 02:37.589
- ZACH: The question's what
the report is called.

02:37.591 --> 02:38.924
And it's so she
can make a point.

02:38.926 --> 02:40.292
- So, can we just
get to the point?

02:40.294 --> 02:41.660
- JOSHUA: You guys
are on the same side.

02:41.662 --> 02:43.028
He's voting the same
as she is, isn't he?

02:43.030 --> 02:44.530
- Yeah, but Joe's not
gonna want to sit here

02:44.532 --> 02:46.532
for an extra hour discussing
what a line item

02:46.534 --> 02:47.332
should be called.

02:47.334 --> 02:48.534
- ZACH: I'm not on the same side

02:48.536 --> 02:50.035
and it's not a line item,
it's a report.

02:50.037 --> 02:52.638
- Um, yes, we are,
and yes it is.

02:52.640 --> 02:54.673
- Lauren? Are Fletcher
and Mihevc both backing?

02:54.675 --> 02:56.842
- LAUREN: What?
- Zach's voting same as me.

02:56.844 --> 02:57.976
- Is that a question?

02:57.978 --> 02:59.111
- It shouldn't be.

02:59.113 --> 03:00.646
- I'm sorry, I'm
not following here.

03:00.648 --> 03:02.381
- Are Mihevc and Fletcher voting
with Catracchia. Guys, come on.

03:02.383 --> 03:03.782
- LAUREN: I mean, I hope so?

03:03.784 --> 03:05.150
- Is that a question?

03:05.152 --> 03:07.853
- Sorry. What's the--
what's the, um, issue here?

03:07.855 --> 03:10.389
- Claire isn't sure
if we're voting the same.

03:10.391 --> 03:13.091
- No, Zachary, I'm sure.

03:13.093 --> 03:14.560
- No, I mean, what issue
are we discussing?

03:14.562 --> 03:17.429
Is it, um, heritage designation?
Where are we?

03:17.431 --> 03:18.397
- Someone make a beer run?

03:18.666 --> 03:19.698
- It's past nine.

03:19.700 --> 03:21.800
- Why are we arguing
about office expenses--

03:21.802 --> 03:24.736
- Office expenses! Yes, um, we
are voting the same. Same vote.

03:24.738 --> 03:26.271
- KAMAL: We should all
make a motion to allow

03:26.273 --> 03:28.040
convenience stores
to sell booze.

03:28.042 --> 03:29.641
Isn't that what
the people want?

03:29.643 --> 03:30.909
- Maybe your people.

03:30.911 --> 03:33.712
- Your people? Is that a racist
thing or an elitist thing?

03:33.714 --> 03:35.581
- Uh, it's provincial.

03:35.583 --> 03:37.382
- Oh, so the opposite
of elitist?

03:37.384 --> 03:39.518
- Uh, booze laws
are provincial,

03:39.520 --> 03:41.820
as in the province handles it.

03:41.822 --> 03:43.755
No one uses the other
"provincial" anymore,

03:43.757 --> 03:46.558
unless you're an elitist,
which apparently you are.

03:46.560 --> 03:48.260
Better not let
your boss find out

03:48.262 --> 03:50.629
he's got an east coast-valued
elitist in his ranks

03:50.631 --> 03:53.131
who's using words
like "provincial"

03:53.133 --> 03:55.400
when words like "hick"
exist in 2012.

03:55.402 --> 03:57.736
- So you're just
skipping over me.

03:57.738 --> 04:00.806
- Is there anything in there
you want to run by us, Zach?

04:00.808 --> 04:03.942
- Well, you guys'll
just nay-say it, so--

04:03.944 --> 04:05.277
- Then I wouldn't run it by us.

04:05.279 --> 04:06.979
- We're saying each
councillor should be given

04:06.981 --> 04:10.182
an increase of $1,000 to
their office budget each month.

04:10.184 --> 04:11.783
- We have 45 offices.

04:11.785 --> 04:14.519
- By office, are we saying the
actual physical structure...

04:14.521 --> 04:16.088
- That's 45 grand a month.

04:16.090 --> 04:18.023
<i> ...or "office"</i> like how we
refer to the White House?

04:18.025 --> 04:19.558
- 540-thousand a year.

04:19.560 --> 04:21.493
- Wait, why are we talking
about the White House?

04:21.495 --> 04:23.328
- How many physical
offices do you count, Zach?

04:23.330 --> 04:25.931
- I just think we need to
clarify if the change applies to

04:25.933 --> 04:28.400
the office or the "office".

04:28.402 --> 04:29.401
- Are you serious right now?

04:29.403 --> 04:30.769
- You guys are all
on the same side.

04:30.771 --> 04:32.471
- Who cares what the
report is called?

04:32.473 --> 04:34.673
- If it sounds like it's just
for a physical office space

04:34.675 --> 04:37.142
and we use it for
office travel expenses,

04:37.144 --> 04:39.678
we're going to get
mini-crucified.

04:40.180 --> 04:41.880
- Oh...

04:42.783 --> 04:44.383
Okay, I get it now.

04:44.785 --> 04:48.320
Yes, no, we do need
to clarify that, guys.

04:48.322 --> 04:50.088
- Look, Claire,

04:50.090 --> 04:51.490
Fletcher and Joe
are going to argue about

04:51.492 --> 04:52.858
what the report is called
to try to justify

04:52.860 --> 04:56.161
using $500,000 which we
already cut from the budget

04:56.163 --> 04:57.596
and people are
happy about it.

04:57.598 --> 04:59.665
And people are actually
happy with the government!

04:59.667 --> 05:02.100
You'll say, that this is
better for the people somehow

05:02.102 --> 05:03.235
but all the people--

05:03.237 --> 05:04.636
that's you and me,

05:04.638 --> 05:06.605
I'm not speaking
councillor-speak here, guys,

05:06.607 --> 05:08.840
I just care about
paying less taxes.

05:08.842 --> 05:10.042
I can't pay my phone bill.

05:10.044 --> 05:11.977
I don't want to pay more taxes
for office expenses

05:11.979 --> 05:14.446
and you guys are going
to try to rename a report

05:14.448 --> 05:16.281
so that you can use
money which we don't have

05:16.283 --> 05:17.783
to use for your office?

05:17.785 --> 05:19.017
- But--
- Yes, Zach.

05:19.019 --> 05:21.620
Conceptual "office" like
The White House or 10 Downing

05:21.622 --> 05:24.222
or whatever the fuck
our equivalent is.

05:24.224 --> 05:26.325
- You know, my long
distance is insane

05:26.327 --> 05:29.194
and I bet the White House
uses their office expenses

05:29.196 --> 05:30.796
to pay for their
assistants' phone bill.

05:30.798 --> 05:32.564
- The White House calls
Russia once a week.

05:32.566 --> 05:34.566
- Yeah, I'm pretty sure
that Obama and Putin

05:34.568 --> 05:36.668
are not having a weekly
catch-up sesh.

05:36.670 --> 05:38.203
- The furthest you
should be calling

05:38.205 --> 05:40.939
for your municipal councillor is
seven blocks from your office.

05:40.941 --> 05:42.441
- Physical, Zach.

05:43.077 --> 05:46.211
- Can we please just figure out
how to bring this city together

05:46.213 --> 05:48.046
and allow convenience
stores to sell alcohol

05:48.048 --> 05:49.948
whenever people want so that
we don't have to spend

05:49.950 --> 05:52.284
10 bucks on a beer whenever
the government liquor stores

05:52.286 --> 05:53.385
are closed?

05:53.387 --> 05:54.720
- ALL: Cheers! Cheers!

05:54.722 --> 05:55.787
- Thank you.

05:58.158 --> 05:59.858
(percussive score continues)

06:17.745 --> 06:19.611
- BRAM: Sorry, hi, I have an
interview. Can I just--

06:19.613 --> 06:21.279
- GIRL IN LINE:
There's a line, buddy.

06:21.281 --> 06:22.581
- Yeah, no, no,
I know. I just--

06:22.583 --> 06:24.850
- Wanted to butt the line?

06:27.121 --> 06:28.086
(sighs)

06:28.088 --> 06:29.287
- I don't know if
butting the line

06:29.289 --> 06:30.655
is a thing past
elementary school.

06:30.657 --> 06:32.391
- It's not.

06:34.461 --> 06:35.761
- JASON: Hey, man.

06:35.763 --> 06:37.295
Thought the only lines
you did are the fun ones.

06:37.297 --> 06:38.630
- Trigger warning: lines.

06:38.632 --> 06:40.098
- Trigger warning: douchebags.

06:40.100 --> 06:41.333
- Oh, trigger warning:

06:41.335 --> 06:42.367
girl who petitioned
for trigger warnings.

06:42.369 --> 06:43.602
- Triggers are
the new spoilers.

06:43.604 --> 06:45.837
- Spoiler alert:
your bro's a prick.

06:45.839 --> 06:47.439
- Okay, if you didn't know
that literally anything

06:47.441 --> 06:48.774
by Sylvia Plath
was about suicide,

06:48.776 --> 06:50.108
you shouldn't have been
in fourth year literature.

06:50.110 --> 06:51.009
- JASON: Multiple spoiler alert.

06:51.011 --> 06:52.177
- Next?

06:52.179 --> 06:53.378
- Can you let
these two go ahead

06:53.380 --> 06:55.180
so I don't need to stand
in front of them any more?

06:55.182 --> 06:56.882
- Yeah, thank you.

06:57.117 --> 06:58.083
- THE MOUSE: Name?

06:58.085 --> 06:59.684
- Bram Shriver.

07:00.888 --> 07:03.088
- Let me see here...
When did you register?

07:03.390 --> 07:04.823
- For what?

07:04.825 --> 07:06.124
- Convocation.

07:06.126 --> 07:08.326
- Uh, when I registered
to study here for four years

07:08.328 --> 07:09.461
and then graduate?

07:09.463 --> 07:11.630
- You have to
register to graduate.

07:11.632 --> 07:13.632
- Okay, so when you register
every year as a student

07:13.634 --> 07:15.434
they don't, uh, the school
doesn't realize

07:15.436 --> 07:17.402
that you would like to
graduate when you finish?

07:17.404 --> 07:19.237
- You have to declare
your intention to graduate

07:19.239 --> 07:20.672
at convocation.

07:20.673 --> 07:22.106
- Does anyone go here with
the intention of not graduating?

07:22.276 --> 07:23.675
- You're still a graduate.

07:23.677 --> 07:25.343
You just aren't
going to graduate,

07:25.345 --> 07:26.978
if that makes sense.

07:27.448 --> 07:30.081
- It doesn't. Um, who do
I have to declare it to?

07:30.083 --> 07:31.349
- You go online
and declare.

07:31.351 --> 07:32.651
- That seems antiquated.

07:32.653 --> 07:34.453
- They've been doing it
since forever.

07:34.455 --> 07:36.455
- Oh, really, so the
five graduates of 1886

07:36.457 --> 07:38.490
went online to register
for convocation?

07:39.026 --> 07:41.226
- If you didn't know you had to
register for graduation,

07:41.228 --> 07:42.294
then you shouldn't
be graduating.

07:42.296 --> 07:43.662
You just won't get
your diploma at the ceremony

07:43.664 --> 07:44.896
because you won't be there.

07:44.898 --> 07:46.598
- Okay, well, it's not
a diploma, actually,

07:46.600 --> 07:49.267
it's a degree because we're
not graduating from high school.

07:49.870 --> 07:51.736
God, how should I break this
to my parents?

07:51.738 --> 07:52.971
- Well, they're
already disappointed

07:52.973 --> 07:54.539
you're not gonna be
a doctor or a lawyer,

07:54.541 --> 07:55.907
so the fact that you're not
graduating, like officially,

07:55.909 --> 07:57.509
as a journalist
probably won't matter.

07:57.511 --> 07:58.743
- I already bought them
graduation tickets.

07:58.745 --> 08:00.512
My mother has been
prepping by researching

08:00.514 --> 08:02.314
Jewish journalists.

08:02.316 --> 08:03.915
- You have to buy tickets?

08:03.917 --> 08:05.050
- Jason Bradley.

08:05.052 --> 08:06.451
(applause)

08:06.453 --> 08:08.687
(gentle score)

08:36.116 --> 08:37.549
(score fades out)

08:37.551 --> 08:39.017
(door opens)

08:39.019 --> 08:40.452
- DAVID: Bram?

08:40.454 --> 08:42.287
Come on back.

08:43.123 --> 08:43.855
- Hey.

08:46.727 --> 08:48.627
(loud industrial machinery)

09:11.718 --> 09:13.552
- Come on in.
- Thanks.

09:13.554 --> 09:15.253
- Take a seat.

09:17.491 --> 09:19.558
Uh, so, you know
my sister-in-law?

09:20.127 --> 09:22.227
- Oh, well, I mean,
my mom's friends with Deb,

09:22.229 --> 09:23.929
so I don't, ah,

09:24.231 --> 09:25.931
know her, but...

09:26.333 --> 09:27.332
Yeah.

09:27.334 --> 09:29.301
- Okay. So other than

09:29.303 --> 09:31.303
sort-of-knowing Deb,
what should I know about you.

09:31.305 --> 09:33.972
- Uh, well, I went to
Western for undergrad and--

09:33.974 --> 09:37.576
- No, no. I got all that.
I read the resumé.

09:37.578 --> 09:39.678
You're a writer.

09:41.415 --> 09:43.114
Pitch me.

09:46.353 --> 09:48.053
- Yeah, um--

09:48.188 --> 09:49.487
(door opens)

09:49.489 --> 09:50.822
- JILL: Hello?

09:50.824 --> 09:52.724
- BRAM: What's for dinner?

09:53.427 --> 09:55.126
- So...?

09:57.631 --> 09:59.297
Aah!
- Hmm.

09:59.299 --> 10:00.332
- Awww.

10:00.334 --> 10:01.499
- PHIL: Good hug or bad hug?

10:01.501 --> 10:03.068
- Aww, are there bad hugs?

10:03.070 --> 10:03.969
- PHIL/BRAM: Yes.

10:03.971 --> 10:05.303
- Here, here, come here,
let me see.

10:05.305 --> 10:08.206
- I already signed it.
- Ah. I'm just reading it.

10:08.208 --> 10:09.240
Ah-ha.

10:09.242 --> 10:10.842
- Yeah, I read it.

10:10.844 --> 10:12.477
- You read they're not
paying your taxes?

10:12.479 --> 10:13.511
- Mm-hm.

10:13.513 --> 10:14.846
- No benefits either, Jill?

10:14.848 --> 10:16.081
- Okay, well, the only
benefit I considered

10:16.083 --> 10:17.749
when someone said "we'll
pay you money to work for us"

10:17.751 --> 10:19.618
is that in a couple of months
I can move out.

10:19.620 --> 10:21.653
- Do you know how much
a house is?

10:21.655 --> 10:23.321
- You know what, at this point,
I would've taken it

10:23.323 --> 10:24.556
if they offered me a Metropass.

10:24.558 --> 10:25.924
- They're not paying
for your Metropass?

10:25.926 --> 10:27.392
- I'm not buying a
house anytime soon.

10:27.394 --> 10:28.893
- Yeah, well, maybe slow down
on the four-dollar coffees.

10:28.895 --> 10:30.128
- Who's here?

10:30.129 --> 10:31.362
- How many days would I
have to give up coffee for

10:31.365 --> 10:32.430
in order to get into
the market?

10:32.432 --> 10:33.798
- SAMMI: Hi!
- PHIL: It's a down payment.

10:33.800 --> 10:34.933
- This is a surprise!

10:34.934 --> 10:36.067
- What was the downpayment
here 25 years ago?

10:36.069 --> 10:37.569
- Well, things were different.
You still have to save.

10:37.571 --> 10:38.570
- Bram got a job.

10:38.572 --> 10:39.738
- Like, a real one?

10:39.740 --> 10:42.807
- Yes, um, and I am
marrying a doctor

10:42.809 --> 10:45.410
and I'm going for lunch every
day before my afternoon nap.

10:45.412 --> 10:47.078
- Mmm, Mom set me
up with my job, too.

10:47.080 --> 10:49.681
- And if I give up my $4-a-day
coffee habit, then I can

10:49.683 --> 10:53.084
save up to buy a million dollar
tear-down in 684 years.

10:53.086 --> 10:55.887
- Wow, I'm sure
Wolf Blitzer has a house.

10:55.889 --> 10:57.389
- Yeah, that he bought
in the roaring 20s.

10:57.391 --> 10:59.090
- And Bernstein?
He's a journalist

10:59.092 --> 11:00.725
and he bought a house.

11:00.727 --> 11:02.661
- We are pregnant.

11:02.663 --> 11:04.663
- Oh, my God.
- What? Ahh!

11:04.665 --> 11:05.730
- Oh, Mazel Tov.

11:05.732 --> 11:07.265
(laughter) Such nachas...

11:07.267 --> 11:10.969
- Oh, I can't believe that my
baby's going to raise her baby!

11:10.971 --> 11:13.304
- I know. I can't believe it.

11:13.306 --> 11:15.407
- PHIL: I knew it, I knew it.

11:15.409 --> 11:16.708
- Nothing?

11:16.710 --> 11:18.510
- That's great. Mazel Tov!

11:18.512 --> 11:20.311
- Thank you, Uncle Bram.

11:20.547 --> 11:22.147
Thanks.

11:23.383 --> 11:24.716
- I feel fat.

11:24.718 --> 11:26.518
- I know, I felt
it when I hugged ya'.

11:26.520 --> 11:28.119
(Phil laughs)

11:28.121 --> 11:29.821
(rock score begins)

11:50.877 --> 11:52.444
- GIDDA: Stop the gravy train.

11:52.446 --> 11:53.445
(laughter)

11:53.447 --> 11:55.180
- You got it, Gidda.

11:57.084 --> 11:58.583
(knocks on door)

11:58.585 --> 12:00.852
(Gidda speaks Arabic)

12:08.261 --> 12:09.994
- Oh, uh...

12:15.535 --> 12:17.235
- Hi, Gidda!

12:18.238 --> 12:19.437
Tell her I say hi.

12:19.439 --> 12:21.506
- Hi, Hi. I understand. Hi.

12:22.075 --> 12:23.141
- Hi.

12:23.143 --> 12:25.210
- Ah, Gidda, Claire's
going to take you home.

12:27.681 --> 12:29.314
- The new girl's
waiting for you.

12:29.316 --> 12:30.815
- Right. Thanks.

12:30.817 --> 12:32.517
(percussive score begins)

12:39.226 --> 12:41.192
- He's already there. He
was supposed to get there later

12:41.194 --> 12:43.228
but he left early.
He does that sometimes.

12:43.230 --> 12:44.295
- ASHLEY: Okay.

12:44.297 --> 12:45.797
- Everyone's gonna be
taking pictures with him

12:45.799 --> 12:47.165
and posting them and saying
what they're gonna say

12:47.167 --> 12:48.733
but we have to make sure
it's organized around him.

12:48.735 --> 12:50.268
- Sure.
- He's easy.

12:50.270 --> 12:52.771
Everybody's got their own thing
with him but he's a good guy.

12:52.773 --> 12:54.572
- "Wieners come in all
shapes and sizes."

12:54.574 --> 12:56.141
You should lead with that.

12:56.143 --> 12:57.108
(laughter)

12:57.110 --> 12:59.043
- THE MOUSE: You the list guy?

12:59.045 --> 13:00.311
These go best
with what you got.

13:00.313 --> 13:02.313
- MANAGER: The list man.
She treating you okay?

13:02.315 --> 13:03.248
- BRAM: Yeah.

13:03.250 --> 13:05.950
- Make sure you say it,
best service.

13:07.154 --> 13:09.020
- Thanks, yeah.

13:09.589 --> 13:11.156
- I wanna write lists.

13:11.158 --> 13:13.825
- How about you go to the next
place and I'll go to the party?

13:13.827 --> 13:16.094
- Okay, here: "Hot dog race:
wiener takes all".

13:16.096 --> 13:17.328
- WAISGLASS: I thought
Jill told my mom

13:17.330 --> 13:18.696
that you started doing
city hall this week.

13:18.698 --> 13:20.165
- Classic Jill.
She also told my mom

13:20.167 --> 13:22.233
that Sammi's kid started walking
before any of his friends.

13:22.235 --> 13:23.902
- Well, now, according
to my mother, um,

13:23.904 --> 13:25.503
he tap-danced
out of the womb.

13:25.505 --> 13:26.938
She is the best publicist.

13:26.940 --> 13:28.273
No, I don't do city hall.

13:28.275 --> 13:29.974
- He's paid to be the
mayor's biggest fanboy.

13:29.976 --> 13:31.342
- A couple of months ago

13:31.344 --> 13:33.077
he decided he didn't want to
talk to press anymore.

13:33.079 --> 13:35.947
- So the press he likes
must really like him now.

13:35.949 --> 13:37.682
- This is what we
gotta work around.

13:37.684 --> 13:38.917
How do we have them
not asking questions

13:38.919 --> 13:40.118
without flat-out saying--

13:40.120 --> 13:42.053
- Doesn't he just flat-out
say most things?

13:42.055 --> 13:43.688
- Saying you can't ask
the mayor questions.

13:43.690 --> 13:45.790
- So there's this assault on the
papers that he doesn't like,

13:45.792 --> 13:46.724
ours included...

13:46.726 --> 13:48.092
- Saying you guys
are bad at your job?

13:48.094 --> 13:49.394
- He doesn't know
he's messing with

13:49.396 --> 13:50.495
a Frum Medal-winning graduate.

13:50.497 --> 13:52.096
- The news isn't accurate
unless he likes it.

13:52.098 --> 13:54.232
And the news that he does like
isn't always accurate.

13:54.234 --> 13:56.301
And then they
came up with this-

13:56.303 --> 13:57.635
this really ridiculous--

13:57.637 --> 13:59.437
- Genius idea.

13:59.439 --> 14:01.606
Don't give them Rob's
schedule every morning.

14:02.509 --> 14:04.108
- They have to chase you.

14:04.110 --> 14:05.710
- The papers are always behind

14:05.712 --> 14:07.178
because we don't know
what to cover each day.

14:07.180 --> 14:09.147
Well, except for the ones
that write the puff pieces,

14:09.149 --> 14:10.181
they know what's happening.

14:10.183 --> 14:11.516
- This is on your work, right?

14:11.518 --> 14:13.051
- Yeah, work perks, my friend.

14:13.053 --> 14:14.819
- So, the Frum Medal-winning,
top-of-his-class

14:14.821 --> 14:16.487
journalism major that
you are currently splitting

14:16.489 --> 14:19.424
a knackwurst with was just
promoted from list-writer.

14:19.426 --> 14:21.459
- 14 bucks for a hot dog?
We should get jobs here.

14:21.461 --> 14:22.393
- So, what are you now?

14:22.395 --> 14:23.461
- Oh, I'm I'm still list writer.

14:23.463 --> 14:25.129
But I'm also the guy
that reverse-engineers

14:25.131 --> 14:27.432
Rob Ford's schedule by
checking his Instagram,

14:27.434 --> 14:29.267
Facebook and Twitter accounts
for his daily whereabouts

14:29.269 --> 14:31.469
and I deliver those reports
to my boss every morning

14:31.471 --> 14:33.638
so that he can give those
stories to everyone but me

14:33.640 --> 14:35.173
as I go off to rate
some hot dogs.

14:35.175 --> 14:37.775
- Okay, but what happens
when some frat bro

14:37.777 --> 14:40.478
posts a picture of
him taking a funnel?

14:40.480 --> 14:42.113
- We bury it. Rob does.

14:42.115 --> 14:44.182
You blacklist a paper and
that becomes their story.

14:44.184 --> 14:46.050
"Assault on us!
Free speech!"

14:46.052 --> 14:48.753
But their free speech becomes
speechifying about their own

14:48.755 --> 14:50.788
personal losses,
not the people's.

14:50.790 --> 14:52.323
So the people don't care.

14:52.325 --> 14:53.925
- I'm basically playing
"Where's Waldo"

14:53.927 --> 14:55.326
with a very large Waldo

14:55.328 --> 14:58.162
until I see something that
I can force my way into.

14:58.164 --> 15:00.131
- Okay, we better
get our buns moving.

15:00.133 --> 15:02.066
- But you also
still do the lists?

15:02.068 --> 15:03.534
- Did you enjoy
your free meal?

15:03.536 --> 15:05.837
- The people must know the
ten best sausages in the city.

15:05.839 --> 15:07.305
Give this place top prize.

15:07.307 --> 15:08.806
- Yeah, bonus points
for their ad spend.

15:08.808 --> 15:10.341
- Whatever happened
to church and state?

15:10.343 --> 15:11.843
- Total clicks.

15:11.845 --> 15:13.044
- You can't come?

15:13.046 --> 15:14.345
- Hot dog tour awaits.

15:14.347 --> 15:15.280
- Ketchup later.

15:15.282 --> 15:17.282
- Yeah, I relish
the opportunity.

15:23.790 --> 15:25.490
Thank you.

15:26.993 --> 15:28.693
(loud club music)

15:29.996 --> 15:32.230
- When are you
supposed to stop him?

15:32.232 --> 15:33.097
- I'm not.

15:33.099 --> 15:34.465
- You're not going to
stop him?

15:34.467 --> 15:35.700
- I'm not supposed to.

15:35.702 --> 15:37.201
- Isn't that your job?

15:37.203 --> 15:38.736
- Not in my job description.

15:38.738 --> 15:39.771
- Actually, it's
part of yours.

15:39.773 --> 15:40.705
- My what?

15:40.707 --> 15:41.839
- Job description.

15:41.841 --> 15:42.807
- To cut him off?

15:42.809 --> 15:44.008
- To make sure no one knows

15:44.010 --> 15:45.910
people thought he
needed to be cut off.

15:45.912 --> 15:47.211
- We should've had
people sign an NDA

15:47.213 --> 15:48.613
when they bought tickets.

15:48.615 --> 15:51.582
- Or confiscated their phones.
Don't look at Instagram.

15:51.584 --> 15:52.951
- Can you imagine the uproar?

15:52.953 --> 15:54.919
- I don't think anybody
cares about signing an NDA.

15:54.921 --> 15:56.454
- No, no, I mean if we'd
taken their phones.

15:56.456 --> 15:58.756
- So what do you do if he does
something embarrassing?

15:58.758 --> 15:59.991
- Do you wanna
take this one?

15:59.993 --> 16:02.994
- Nah. Let her see
the master at work.

16:04.331 --> 16:05.830
- Ask me again.

16:06.466 --> 16:09.734
- What do you do if he does
something embarrassing?

16:10.070 --> 16:13.838
- The media is always
out to embarrass our mayor.

16:13.840 --> 16:16.240
Note the use of "our"
instead of "the" mayor

16:16.242 --> 16:18.476
even while he's
fighting -- key word

16:18.478 --> 16:19.877
he's up against the enemy,

16:19.879 --> 16:21.512
sword and shield,
taking down the dragons.

16:21.514 --> 16:24.282
To help the working taxpayers
of this great city,

16:24.284 --> 16:27.852
see their money working for them
instead of lining the pockets

16:27.854 --> 16:29.454
of special interest cronies.

16:29.456 --> 16:31.990
That tells them that there's
this cabal of rich dudes

16:31.992 --> 16:33.891
pulling the strings
for the other guys.

16:33.893 --> 16:36.194
Now, do you know what's
truly embarrassing?

16:36.196 --> 16:38.062
No, Anderson,
don't cut me off.

16:38.064 --> 16:39.897
I'm not finished.
Here's where we put the person

16:39.899 --> 16:42.033
asking the question on defense.

16:42.035 --> 16:45.370
That you're focusing
on whether our mayor --

16:45.372 --> 16:46.471
check --

16:46.473 --> 16:48.206
grabbed a beer with
his friends last night --

16:48.208 --> 16:49.474
the everyman, check --

16:49.476 --> 16:52.043
while the mayor's opponents --
the dragons --

16:52.045 --> 16:55.013
are, at this very moment
proposing spending increases

16:55.015 --> 16:57.715
in support of themselves
and their donors --

16:57.717 --> 16:59.984
secret cabal, check-check --

16:59.986 --> 17:03.254
at the expense
of the taxpayer.

17:03.256 --> 17:04.789
(laughing)

17:04.991 --> 17:06.991
- They don't call us
special assistants for nothing.

17:06.993 --> 17:08.893
(glasses clink)

17:08.895 --> 17:10.595
(church bell tolls)

17:14.034 --> 17:15.733
(cell phone vibrates)

17:16.036 --> 17:17.435
(cell phone vibrates)

17:17.437 --> 17:19.370
(cell phone chimes
and vibrates)

17:19.372 --> 17:20.772
(sighing)

17:20.774 --> 17:22.673
(score begins)

17:23.543 --> 17:25.777
- PHIL: Whatever it is, push to
write about it. Be aggressive.

17:25.779 --> 17:26.844
- I know.

17:26.846 --> 17:28.279
- You won the Frum Medal!

17:28.281 --> 17:29.547
Tell them.

17:29.549 --> 17:31.249
- They know. Bye.

17:38.291 --> 17:40.992
- Dave, hey. I was just
coming to find you.

17:40.994 --> 17:42.060
- Well, you found me.
What's up?

17:42.062 --> 17:43.728
- Oh, I wanted to talk
to you about this story.

17:43.730 --> 17:44.896
- Talk.

17:44.898 --> 17:46.364
- It's this story
I want to show you.

17:46.366 --> 17:48.733
- So show me. Talk or
show, Bram. Talk or show.

17:48.735 --> 17:49.901
- Okay.

17:49.903 --> 17:51.102
- Hey, you hear about
the CJPAC party?

17:51.104 --> 17:52.470
- Yeah, I spoke to Nelson.
They're denying.

17:52.472 --> 17:54.505
I'll speak with her and
anyone else who was there

17:54.507 --> 17:56.507
who's gonna talk
but it was open bar.

17:56.509 --> 17:57.508
- Speak with who?

17:57.510 --> 17:59.210
- So what, what does that mean?
Who cares.

17:59.212 --> 18:02.547
- It's a bunch of dumb kids,
politicians and unlimited booze,

18:02.549 --> 18:04.182
we're not going to get
anything reliable.

18:04.184 --> 18:05.516
Not on record, anyway.

18:05.518 --> 18:07.018
- Try.

18:07.020 --> 18:08.052
- Wait, what is that story?

18:08.054 --> 18:09.554
- Susan's on it.
What did you wanna show me?

18:09.556 --> 18:11.389
- I could do it with her.
What's, what's it?

18:11.391 --> 18:12.807
- Ooh!

18:12.808 --> 18:14.224
As much as she'd love that,
we have you on something else.

18:14.227 --> 18:18.129
Uhh, where is it?
Best brunch spots in the city.

18:18.598 --> 18:20.865
- Yeah. Um, I mean...

18:21.868 --> 18:23.534
Dave, just, the thing is, just

18:23.536 --> 18:24.969
I've been working for
more than a year now--

18:24.971 --> 18:26.337
- I know.

18:26.339 --> 18:28.439
- You know? And I just was,
I was wondering if...

18:28.441 --> 18:30.308
I'm still doing the same thing.
Which is, that's--

18:30.310 --> 18:32.310
I don't mind doing that...
I like that stuff,

18:32.312 --> 18:34.946
I just, I think
that I could be...

18:34.948 --> 18:37.748
really useful with
this sort of thing, too.

18:38.251 --> 18:40.785
- You're a reporter.
You report on things.

18:41.020 --> 18:42.286
- Lists.

18:42.288 --> 18:44.088
- You know you don't get
to be editor on day two

18:44.090 --> 18:45.590
just 'cuz you showed up
on day one.

18:45.592 --> 18:47.058
- I-I know.

18:47.060 --> 18:48.126
- Do you?

18:48.128 --> 18:49.994
People read lists.
They read them.

18:49.996 --> 18:52.029
You remember when the Huffington
Post used to have real news?

18:52.031 --> 18:53.998
- BuzzFeed does real news now
so can I just, can I just--

18:54.000 --> 18:55.766
- No one who actually
cares about the news

18:55.768 --> 18:57.335
looks for it on the
sidebar of

18:57.337 --> 19:00.438
"The 15 Paperweights That'll
Restore Your Faith in Beyonce."

19:00.440 --> 19:03.975
- Well, I'll-I'll still
do the brunch thing, I just...

19:04.144 --> 19:05.843
That's...

19:06.946 --> 19:08.813
I mean, I won the Frum Medal.

19:08.815 --> 19:10.448
- Oh, Jesus Christ.

19:13.253 --> 19:15.286
Go do some streeters!

19:15.288 --> 19:17.188
About the CJPAC thing.

19:19.926 --> 19:21.325
(score begins)

19:21.327 --> 19:22.827
- So, last night,
Rob Ford was at an event

19:22.829 --> 19:25.596
where he was accused of groping
a former mayoral candidate.

19:25.598 --> 19:27.398
How do you feel like this
reflects on the city?

19:27.400 --> 19:29.066
- BLACK TOQUE MAN: He likes
to have a good time.

19:29.068 --> 19:30.468
I like to have a good time.

19:30.470 --> 19:32.069
- FUR WOMAN: Well. It's gross.

19:32.071 --> 19:33.471
- YELLOW COAT WOMAN: You guys,

19:33.473 --> 19:35.306
it's just non-stop
with this guy.

19:35.308 --> 19:36.741
Just let him do his job.

19:36.742 --> 19:38.175
- Excuse me, sir, can I ask you
just a quick question about--

19:38.178 --> 19:39.877
- MOHAWK MAN: Don't give a fuck.

19:39.879 --> 19:41.362
- Thank you.

19:41.363 --> 19:42.846
Can I ask you a quick question
about the Mayor real quick?

19:42.849 --> 19:43.881
- ORANGE TOQUE GUY: High school.

19:43.883 --> 19:45.283
- That's right.
- Bram.

19:45.285 --> 19:47.285
- How are you, man?
- Good.

19:47.287 --> 19:48.419
Is this what
you're doing now?

19:48.421 --> 19:49.854
- Like, really, who cares?

19:49.856 --> 19:51.389
- I mean, groping or not,

19:51.391 --> 19:53.591
it's believeable and it's gross
and that's what's wrong with it.

19:53.593 --> 19:56.694
- Do you get paid for this
or is it, like, volunteer?

19:56.696 --> 19:57.895
- Who cares?

19:57.897 --> 20:00.164
- I don't remember the
question but I have to go.

20:00.166 --> 20:01.432
- Word. Okay.
- See you later.

20:01.434 --> 20:03.868
- Say "Hi" to your mom.
- Yep.

20:04.704 --> 20:06.504
(score ends)

20:08.241 --> 20:11.108
- Excuse-- Excuse me, sir?
Could you just-- Could you--

20:11.110 --> 20:13.911
Do you want to answer
a quick question?

20:17.717 --> 20:19.116
Okay.

20:19.118 --> 20:20.818
(flags flapping in wind)

20:27.994 --> 20:29.527
- Seeing as how
a mere three days later,

20:29.529 --> 20:32.230
there's not a front page
mention of Gropegate--

20:32.232 --> 20:33.497
- I don't think it's
considered a "-gate"

20:33.499 --> 20:34.899
if it's not even mentioned
three days later.

20:34.901 --> 20:36.033
- Claire?

20:36.035 --> 20:37.301
- Yeah. I don't think
it's a "-gate."

20:37.303 --> 20:38.970
- Overruled!
- Man, let's get this going!

20:38.972 --> 20:40.605
Tonight is a special night

20:40.607 --> 20:43.040
because for the first time in
her young career as an aborted

20:43.042 --> 20:45.009
lawyer-cum-communications
manager

20:45.011 --> 20:48.012
I pass tonight's
City Hall of Fame to...

20:48.014 --> 20:49.480
(drumming)

20:49.482 --> 20:50.915
Ashley!

20:50.917 --> 20:52.116
(cheers)

20:52.118 --> 20:53.484
- For answering that phone
like no other.

20:53.486 --> 20:55.886
- Uh, how many calls redirected
over a two-day period?

20:55.888 --> 20:58.823
- 250-fucking-four.

20:58.825 --> 21:00.224
- Ashley!

21:00.226 --> 21:01.926
(drumming)

21:02.328 --> 21:05.363
Four years of undergrad in --
psychology?

21:05.798 --> 21:07.064
- Classics.
- Ah.

21:07.066 --> 21:09.567
Very practical. Four years
in whatever-the-fuck that is.

21:09.569 --> 21:11.369
Another three floating
smack in the middle

21:11.371 --> 21:12.737
of your law-school class,

21:12.739 --> 21:14.405
seeing your entire Facebook
doing better than you

21:14.407 --> 21:16.240
at everything and you too

21:16.242 --> 21:18.576
can have a job that most
forward-thinking companies

21:18.578 --> 21:20.978
have replaced with a machine!

21:20.980 --> 21:22.813
Ashley Pollock, everybody!

21:22.815 --> 21:25.750
- Thank you. All right, yes!

21:25.752 --> 21:27.118
Thank you so much.

21:27.120 --> 21:30.221
Thank you, thank you,
thank you. Yes.

21:30.223 --> 21:31.322
- Congratulations.

21:31.324 --> 21:33.024
- Thank you.

21:33.526 --> 21:36.594
Wow, I wasn't expecting this.

21:36.596 --> 21:37.995
I am so humbled.

21:37.997 --> 21:40.831
Truth is, I can't take
all the credit on this one.

21:40.833 --> 21:44.068
Mostly, I have to thank
a shitload of debt.

21:44.070 --> 21:45.536
Linda, who calls twice a week

21:45.538 --> 21:47.805
and who's not only
my loan officer

21:47.807 --> 21:50.241
but who's also, basically,
my therapist

21:50.243 --> 21:51.842
and personal advisor.

21:51.844 --> 21:53.711
Oh, no the music!

21:53.713 --> 21:56.047
I have to thank
that piece of paper

21:56.049 --> 21:58.182
that's hanging
in my parent's den.

21:58.184 --> 22:00.117
- To Ashley!
(cheers)

22:00.119 --> 22:02.019
(score begins)

22:11.230 --> 22:12.930
(phone ringing)

22:15.601 --> 22:17.101
- Sharma.

22:24.577 --> 22:27.578
- LOWEY: A year ago,
someone recorded a video,

22:29.649 --> 22:31.349
allegedly...

22:32.118 --> 22:33.417
- Of what?

22:33.419 --> 22:35.486
She started working there
a few months ago.

22:35.488 --> 22:36.921
- Why would she know anything?

22:36.923 --> 22:38.556
- Press calls her before
releasing anything.

22:38.558 --> 22:40.024
She's the gatekeeper.

22:40.026 --> 22:41.826
- So the guy selling
the video would call her?

22:41.828 --> 22:44.462
- No. He'd call Kamal but she
may know if the video guy

22:44.464 --> 22:45.963
contacted him first.

22:45.965 --> 22:47.398
- What does Kamal do?

22:47.400 --> 22:49.166
- Special Assistant
to the Mayor.

22:49.168 --> 22:50.334
- And he knows?

22:50.336 --> 22:52.036
- Everything.

22:53.940 --> 22:55.172
(toilet flushing)

22:55.174 --> 22:56.807
- Now, sorry, what's the
difference between

22:56.809 --> 22:59.377
special assistants
and assistants?

22:59.379 --> 23:00.711
- No, they're all special.

23:00.713 --> 23:02.246
- Your mom tell you that, too?

23:02.248 --> 23:04.148
Look, call the girl and tell her

23:04.150 --> 23:06.584
we won't release her name if
that's what she's worried about.

23:06.586 --> 23:08.119
- Oh, Judith Asche
from the paper?

23:08.121 --> 23:09.520
She wants us to come down there.

23:09.522 --> 23:11.622
- Oh yeah, I told her.
It's an internal issue for them.

23:11.624 --> 23:14.191
- It sounds like one of her
guys may have met with our guy.

23:14.193 --> 23:15.893
- Can we call our guy
"the video guy"

23:15.895 --> 23:18.529
so we can keep this all clear?
Who's their guy?

23:18.531 --> 23:19.764
- Which guy are
you talking about?

23:19.766 --> 23:21.899
- The paper's guy.
- Oh, the list guy.

23:21.901 --> 23:23.300
- Yeah. The list guy.

23:23.302 --> 23:24.935
(door locking)

23:24.937 --> 23:26.637
- Fuck.

23:27.874 --> 23:29.573
(tense score begins)

24:06.012 --> 24:09.346
- LOWEY: So you tended to work
on what kind of assignments?

24:09.348 --> 24:11.115
- What nobody else wanted.

24:13.252 --> 24:14.785
Uh,

24:14.787 --> 24:17.688
top ten lists. Best burgers,
best fruit stands.

24:17.690 --> 24:19.857
- But you also knew
everywhere he was gonna be?

24:19.859 --> 24:23.027
- Everywhere he had been.
Or as he was there, maybe.

24:23.029 --> 24:24.962
But never before.

24:24.964 --> 24:27.264
- So how does this video come
your way if you're the guy

24:27.266 --> 24:29.066
making lists of good burgers?

24:30.470 --> 24:32.169
- Downsizing.

24:33.873 --> 24:35.439
- SUSAN: Did you
get one of these?

24:39.045 --> 24:41.178
- No, I-I don't think...

24:41.180 --> 24:43.180
No.

24:59.599 --> 25:01.499
- Susan speaking...

25:01.868 --> 25:03.567
David. Hi.

25:07.006 --> 25:10.708
Listen, David. David.
David, I am not

25:10.710 --> 25:13.344
sitting through a meeting
to go through this.

25:13.346 --> 25:15.045
I'm just not.

25:16.015 --> 25:17.314
This is...

25:17.316 --> 25:18.816
Hm.

25:18.818 --> 25:20.284
Where's Judith?

25:20.286 --> 25:22.620
Because I want to
speak with her.

25:22.755 --> 25:26.023
Ah, no, she wouldn't,
would she? Heaven forbid.

25:29.061 --> 25:32.129
David, I am not coming in
there to put myself through this

25:32.131 --> 25:34.565
to walk out with
a fucking folder

25:34.567 --> 25:37.201
so everybody here
can see, okay?

25:37.203 --> 25:38.903
I'm not.

25:39.605 --> 25:42.806
All right, well, then,
just put whatever it is

25:42.808 --> 25:44.909
in your little folder
in the mail for me, David.

25:44.911 --> 25:47.745
Yes, in the mail,
and I will look it over

25:47.747 --> 25:50.014
with a drink in my hand.

25:52.018 --> 25:53.684
- So...

25:54.754 --> 25:57.021
the guy didn't have a choice?

25:57.390 --> 25:59.657
- Well, I didn't really care.

26:00.426 --> 26:02.359
I got the call.

26:02.361 --> 26:03.994
(phone ringing)

26:03.996 --> 26:05.930
(dramatic score)

26:05.932 --> 26:07.631
(phone ringing)

26:10.202 --> 26:11.902
(phone ringing)

26:14.507 --> 26:16.140
(phone ringing)

26:17.810 --> 26:19.310
- Hello?

26:20.212 --> 26:22.279
Oh, no. Um...

26:23.449 --> 26:25.249
But I can help you.

26:27.820 --> 26:29.320
Bram.

26:32.124 --> 26:33.824
Yeah.

26:34.093 --> 26:35.793
No-no-no-yes, I can meet.

26:36.996 --> 26:38.596
- I just think if they
let this woman go,

26:38.598 --> 26:39.830
you should ask for
a raise. Something.

26:39.832 --> 26:41.065
- Okay, well, they fired her

26:41.067 --> 26:42.266
because they don't want
to pay her anymore.

26:42.268 --> 26:43.934
So I really don't think
they're just going to roll over

26:43.936 --> 26:45.035
whatever savings they've got
on to me.

26:45.037 --> 26:46.570
I don't, I don't want to
discuss it.

26:46.572 --> 26:48.305
- Okay. Okay. We don't
have to discuss it,

26:48.307 --> 26:49.440
but

26:49.442 --> 26:51.442
I just want to say that

26:51.444 --> 26:53.711
I think you're settling.
That's it.

26:55.247 --> 26:55.980
- Okay.

26:57.550 --> 26:58.282
- Okay.

27:00.886 --> 27:02.686
So, that's all you have
to say is okay?

27:02.688 --> 27:03.887
- I thought that we
weren't discussing it.

27:03.889 --> 27:05.589
- We not discussing it.
I'm just...

27:05.591 --> 27:08.292
- We're just gonna keep
the discussion going.

27:08.294 --> 27:09.693
- I'm not the kind of mother

27:09.695 --> 27:11.895
that pressured her son to go to
law school, Bram, okay?

27:11.897 --> 27:13.397
- No, no. You're the kind
that guilts me for

27:13.399 --> 27:14.531
not having thought of it myself.

27:14.533 --> 27:16.266
- And you're still
doing the lists.

27:16.268 --> 27:17.635
- SERVER: Pea soups?

27:17.637 --> 27:20.537
Okay. And the Greek.

27:20.539 --> 27:22.439
Tuna Reuben for the boy's
coming up.

27:22.441 --> 27:24.908
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

27:26.012 --> 27:27.311
I'm just--

27:27.313 --> 27:28.612
(sighs)

27:28.614 --> 27:30.347
You write so well.

27:30.349 --> 27:32.049
You're so smart

27:32.051 --> 27:35.719
and now you're just writing
the-the 20 best things to...

27:35.721 --> 27:39.423
I don't know! The places to make
a candle -- whatever! Oh.

27:39.425 --> 27:41.191
- Well, hm, I got
a story, anyways.

27:41.193 --> 27:42.092
Um,

27:42.094 --> 27:44.595
a guy called and
he wants to meet.

27:44.597 --> 27:46.296
- Oh. About what?

27:46.832 --> 27:48.065
- I guess we'll find out.

27:48.067 --> 27:49.900
- Oh, my God. Where does
he want to meet you?

27:49.902 --> 27:51.735
Actually, don't even tell me.

27:51.737 --> 27:54.271
Just text me afterwards, okay?

27:54.273 --> 27:55.806
Ah.

27:55.808 --> 27:57.608
- Look, you tell your story in
your own words, people listen.

27:57.610 --> 27:59.309
Don't filter. And tell
this David guy,

27:59.311 --> 28:01.712
"I'm pitching it.
It's my story. Don't ask."

28:01.714 --> 28:03.213
- Tuna reuben.
- Thank you.

28:03.215 --> 28:04.915
- Plate's hot.

28:21.067 --> 28:22.766
- Abe.

28:23.135 --> 28:24.635
Hi.

28:24.637 --> 28:26.336
Bram.

28:26.806 --> 28:28.505
- You don't mind?

28:28.674 --> 28:31.041
- No. No no, no. I sh...

28:31.343 --> 28:33.043
Should've brought mine.

28:35.081 --> 28:36.580
So, um,

28:36.582 --> 28:38.549
you called, but,

28:38.684 --> 28:40.984
said you wanted to meet in
person about your story?

28:40.986 --> 28:43.087
- I work in the community.

28:43.089 --> 28:46.557
Normally we are not getting paid
that much attention to.

28:46.559 --> 28:49.293
- Well, I'm happy
to speak with you.

28:49.295 --> 28:51.829
- I saw the lists you write.

28:52.398 --> 28:54.098
I like those.

28:55.034 --> 28:57.134
- Oh. Thanks.

28:57.136 --> 29:00.404
- But, one time, you asked
what people thought

29:01.140 --> 29:04.274
about how the mayor acted
at that thing, yeah?

29:04.276 --> 29:06.844
You know someone said he was

29:06.846 --> 29:09.346
maybe drunk and I wondered...

29:09.348 --> 29:11.148
I was surprised why

29:11.150 --> 29:14.318
no one asked if maybe
it was something else

29:14.320 --> 29:16.920
that made Mr. Ford act that way.

29:17.389 --> 29:19.957
- Well uh, what do you mean
"something else"?

29:19.959 --> 29:22.960
- You're probably thinking,
maybe, what I do.

29:23.562 --> 29:25.162
- Well, I'm actually thinking,

29:25.464 --> 29:28.899
"What do you mean by 'something
else' made him act that way?"

29:28.901 --> 29:30.801
(dryer cycle finished buzzer)

29:34.406 --> 29:35.806
(dramatic score begins)

29:35.808 --> 29:37.841
- Some of these kids I know
don't lead their lives

29:37.843 --> 29:39.543
in the right way.

29:41.747 --> 29:43.447
"Something else."

29:44.049 --> 29:46.250
- I gotta be honest, I have

29:46.252 --> 29:48.886
no clue what you're talking
about or what the story is,

29:48.888 --> 29:51.054
which sort of helps tell it.

29:51.056 --> 29:52.456
(Abe laughs)

29:52.458 --> 29:54.158
(laughter)

30:03.135 --> 30:05.302
- I told them I would help them,

30:05.304 --> 30:08.372
so they don't have to
do this bad stuff.

30:08.541 --> 30:11.542
- I feel like this meeting
needs a Rashi, or something.

30:11.544 --> 30:13.243
- A what?

30:13.813 --> 30:15.546
- Never mind.

30:15.548 --> 30:17.481
(paper unfolding)

30:22.555 --> 30:24.621
What am I looking at?

30:24.957 --> 30:27.324
- For a good story, maybe...

30:27.326 --> 30:29.426
your paper, they pay?

30:34.767 --> 30:36.934
- So, we can't tack anything
on this guy

30:36.936 --> 30:39.236
other than taking a picture
with low-level bangers?

30:39.238 --> 30:40.370
- No, not yet.

30:40.372 --> 30:41.705
- So, who drove him here?

30:41.707 --> 30:42.773
- It could've been his guy.

30:42.775 --> 30:44.374
- Which guy's that?
- Rob's guy.

30:44.376 --> 30:47.110
- Okay, so Rob's guy takes Rob
to visit these guys,

30:47.112 --> 30:49.046
who're using the video
- Alleged.

30:49.048 --> 30:52.783
- Alleged video, thank you,
to sell to the list guy?

30:52.785 --> 30:54.284
- And others, yeah.

30:54.286 --> 30:56.353
- Well, how many
private residences

30:56.355 --> 30:57.855
did this guy drive Rob to?

30:57.857 --> 30:59.456
- Which guy?
- Rob's guy.

30:59.458 --> 31:01.658
- Thousands.
- Thousands?

31:01.660 --> 31:02.860
- Yeah. People
call him everyday.

31:02.862 --> 31:04.895
- And he answered them?
Personally?

31:04.897 --> 31:07.464
- In person.
(phone rings)

31:07.466 --> 31:08.999
(phone rings)

31:09.001 --> 31:10.968
<i> - You've reached the office</i>
<i> of Mayor Rob Ford.</i>

31:10.970 --> 31:13.170
<i> Neither he, nor Special</i>
<i> Assistant, Kamal Arafa</i>

31:13.172 --> 31:14.705
<i> are able to take your call.</i>

31:14.707 --> 31:16.106
<i> If this is a query</i>
<i> for the Mayor,</i>

31:16.108 --> 31:17.741
<i> please leave your name and</i>
<i> number and he will</i>

31:17.743 --> 31:19.610
<i> return your call</i>
<i> within 48 hours.</i>

31:19.612 --> 31:21.578
<i> Go Argos!</i>

31:21.580 --> 31:23.280
(answering machine
recording beep)

31:33.726 --> 31:34.491
- I have something.

31:34.493 --> 31:35.225
- What is it?

31:38.731 --> 31:40.530
- Can I pitch it?
- You are. What is it?

31:40.532 --> 31:42.199
- No, I want to do it
at the desk meeting.

31:42.201 --> 31:43.267
- Huh, no.

31:45.504 --> 31:46.970
- Dave, it's a good story.

31:46.972 --> 31:48.772
- Everyone's story's always
a good story until it's not

31:48.774 --> 31:50.173
and it ends up being bad
when Judith sucks

31:50.175 --> 31:51.592
the air out if it.

31:51.593 --> 31:53.010
- Last time I gave you a
story you gave it to Susan.

31:53.012 --> 31:54.945
- Last time you gave me
a story, I didn't pitch it.

32:09.995 --> 32:11.929
I'm gonna need some context.

32:11.931 --> 32:15.699
- Well, if you like it,
I'm pitching it. It's my story.

32:18.637 --> 32:20.337
(knocking on door)

32:23.375 --> 32:26.009
- Oh! Hey! How are ya?

32:26.011 --> 32:28.812
Hey. How are ya? How ya doing?
What's your name?

32:28.814 --> 32:29.780
- Lauren.

32:29.782 --> 32:32.149
- Huh, Lauren?

32:32.151 --> 32:34.718
A selfie, or... Very good.

32:34.720 --> 32:35.819
- Thank you.

32:35.821 --> 32:38.055
- All right. All right.
You take care.

32:46.532 --> 32:47.264
They home?

32:48.434 --> 32:49.166
- I knocked.

32:49.902 --> 32:50.634
- Here.

33:01.847 --> 33:03.280
Hi, I'm Rob.

33:03.282 --> 33:05.482
You left me a message
on my answering machine.

33:05.484 --> 33:10.120
<i>- Hey, Mayor Ford, uh, my name's</i>
<i>Mark. I live around midtown and</i>

33:10.122 --> 33:12.622
(overlapping indecipherable
voice messages)

33:28.207 --> 33:31.308
- Kamal's got your information.
I'll follow up in a week.

33:31.310 --> 33:33.176
- Uh, we'll try for a week.

33:33.178 --> 33:35.779
It's closer to three weeks,
maybe a month.

33:36.782 --> 33:38.849
- Okay. A month.

33:38.851 --> 33:41.151
- Thanks for the call.
And the support.

33:41.153 --> 33:43.687
<i> - No problem.</i>
- Yeah, yeah, yeah. I, uh...

33:44.523 --> 33:45.255
I appreciate it.

33:51.964 --> 33:53.997
- I don't want you to do that.

33:53.999 --> 33:55.599
When you disagree with me,

33:55.601 --> 33:57.968
you work for me, so you don't
disagree with me.

33:57.970 --> 33:59.269
- I didn't.

33:59.271 --> 34:01.238
- You told them it would be
a month before we got back

34:01.240 --> 34:02.639
to them.

34:02.641 --> 34:04.708
- It is. I told you,
we're backed up on these.

34:04.710 --> 34:06.109
- You didn't remind me!

34:06.111 --> 34:07.511
It's too long!

34:07.513 --> 34:09.980
Look, they voted for me
to fix stuff and you're not!

34:09.982 --> 34:11.615
- Remember, I told you--

34:11.617 --> 34:13.550
- But you didn't tell me.

34:17.589 --> 34:18.855
- We're late.

34:18.857 --> 34:22.592
- Hey, don't get your panties
in a knot. Start the car.

34:36.075 --> 34:37.774
(clearing throat)

34:40.646 --> 34:41.745
- JUDITH: David.

34:41.747 --> 34:43.146
- Mm-hm?

34:43.148 --> 34:45.348
- Why are you two people?

34:45.350 --> 34:46.850
(sighing)

34:47.386 --> 34:48.652
- It's, uh...

34:48.654 --> 34:50.353
His story.

34:51.790 --> 34:53.490
- Okay.

34:55.160 --> 34:57.994
You see how these meetings
work, David, is--

34:58.530 --> 35:00.597
I think you know this because
you're in these meetings

35:00.599 --> 35:02.999
twice a day, every day --
is the desk editor

35:03.001 --> 35:05.602
gathers some options
from their beat to pitch.

35:05.938 --> 35:08.705
Everyone has
someone else's story.

35:08.707 --> 35:11.341
So you brought the kid
with you today, fine, but...

35:11.343 --> 35:13.543
But this tells me one
of two things. Either...

35:13.545 --> 35:14.845
one:

35:14.847 --> 35:16.379
you think this is a big story,

35:16.381 --> 35:19.549
big enough to bring someone in
to corroborate or back you up.

35:19.551 --> 35:21.585
Probably back you up,
I'm thinking.

35:21.587 --> 35:24.855
Or two: the kid's jerking
you off under the table.

35:25.357 --> 35:27.124
(chuckles)

35:28.026 --> 35:29.759
Neither's really
a great option.

35:29.761 --> 35:32.529
In the first case,
your most junior reporter,

35:32.531 --> 35:34.331
who's been here a tenth
of the time than your

35:34.333 --> 35:37.667
next most senior reporter
has been, is scooping people

35:37.669 --> 35:40.170
that we are paying at least
three times more,

35:40.172 --> 35:42.606
and that tells me that
there is still

35:42.608 --> 35:44.341
some fat to be
trimmed at your desk

35:44.343 --> 35:47.844
and you know they are always
looking to trim some fat.

35:48.480 --> 35:50.947
I don't like letting
people go, though,

35:50.949 --> 35:52.883
so, I don't like that option.

35:53.585 --> 35:56.853
But in the second scenario?
The one

35:56.855 --> 36:00.524
where he is jerking you
off at the office, well...

36:00.526 --> 36:03.059
you are being jerked off
and I don't think we pay you

36:03.061 --> 36:04.794
for that, either.

36:04.796 --> 36:06.296
(laughing)

36:06.665 --> 36:08.765
I don't think
you're being jerked off.

36:08.767 --> 36:09.733
- I'm not.

36:09.735 --> 36:11.434
- That's too bad.

36:11.803 --> 36:13.336
(sighing)

36:13.338 --> 36:16.239
But, I don't want to embarrass
the kid by asking him to leave

36:16.241 --> 36:18.942
his first desk meeting,
but it is one rep per desk,

36:18.944 --> 36:21.778
so we'll see you
at the next one, David.

36:24.950 --> 36:26.683
It's his story.

36:27.686 --> 36:29.386
(laughing)

36:32.524 --> 36:34.224
- Fine.

36:42.568 --> 36:44.234
- Wait.

36:45.804 --> 36:47.504
Lynn?

36:47.940 --> 36:49.472
- LYNN: Mirvish is filing suit

36:49.474 --> 36:51.208
against a New York gallery

36:51.210 --> 36:53.777
for purchasing fake Pollocks
ten years ago.

36:53.779 --> 36:55.912
(loud machinery)

37:10.429 --> 37:13.330
- I don't like too many
people in the room.

37:13.332 --> 37:16.233
Everyone'll want to come in
to pitch their story.

37:16.235 --> 37:18.568
There's just not enough time
as it is and

37:18.570 --> 37:21.871
not everyone's story is as
good as they think it is.

37:21.873 --> 37:23.573
As big.

37:26.745 --> 37:27.677
(sighs)

37:27.679 --> 37:29.379
How good is yours?

37:30.849 --> 37:33.583
- Well, now I feel like maybe
it's not as good as I think.

37:33.819 --> 37:35.518
- Don't sandbag. It's obnoxious.

37:39.925 --> 37:41.224
- Yeah, right.

37:41.226 --> 37:42.859
Um, okay. Uh...

37:44.096 --> 37:46.196
- Why are their
eyes blacked out?

37:46.198 --> 37:47.931
- Um, he doesn't want us
to print it

37:47.933 --> 37:49.299
unless we're taking the story.

37:49.301 --> 37:51.101
- We're not taking the story
unless we can see the video.

37:51.103 --> 37:54.638
Otherwise it's-it's just a photo
of him with a bunch of kids.

37:54.640 --> 37:56.506
He takes pictures with
everyone, everywhere.

37:56.508 --> 37:59.943
He's the town's mall Santa,
all year.

37:59.945 --> 38:01.344
How much does
your guy want?

38:01.346 --> 38:04.247
- Uh, he said that someone else
offered them 5,000

38:04.249 --> 38:05.749
and they want more.

38:05.751 --> 38:06.683
- Who?

38:06.685 --> 38:08.385
- He didn't say.

38:08.887 --> 38:10.820
- You think it's real?

38:12.758 --> 38:13.957
- I don't know.

38:13.959 --> 38:15.492
- Here's a new rule: when you're
asked your opinion,

38:15.494 --> 38:16.860
you have to have one.

38:16.862 --> 38:19.729
When you met with your guy--
do you know his name?

38:19.731 --> 38:21.231
- His first name.

38:21.233 --> 38:24.367
- Okay. When you met with him

38:24.369 --> 38:26.936
did you believe that
he was being truthful?

38:28.006 --> 38:29.606
- Yes.

38:32.044 --> 38:33.543
- We're interested,
but not sold.

38:33.545 --> 38:35.245
Tell him. Try and see the video.

38:35.247 --> 38:37.314
- Well, unless we have an offer,
I don't-I don't--

38:37.316 --> 38:39.015
think that will happen.

38:41.620 --> 38:43.953
- Then you don't have a story.

38:43.955 --> 38:45.722
(gentle score begins)

38:56.068 --> 38:57.767
- Rob's not here.

39:01.573 --> 39:03.340
- He left something at Hadi's.

39:03.342 --> 39:05.342
I was just
bringing it back.

39:06.144 --> 39:07.377
- You can leave it with me.

39:11.016 --> 39:14.484
- I was also thinking
maybe I could speak with him?

39:14.720 --> 39:16.419
Maybe.

39:17.556 --> 39:19.689
- You can talk to me.

39:53.125 --> 39:55.759
- Hi! Hey, it's Bram. Um...

39:56.561 --> 39:59.496
Let's, uh, let's meet again,
all right? I can, um...

39:59.498 --> 40:02.799
Just-just try me back or
I'll-I'll-I'll call you again,

40:02.801 --> 40:04.968
I guess, um...

40:04.970 --> 40:06.369
It's Bram, again, it's--

40:06.371 --> 40:08.238
We met at the laundromat.

40:08.240 --> 40:09.939
Um...

40:10.242 --> 40:12.842
Uh, thanks. Okay. Uh, bye.

40:16.014 --> 40:17.414
(notebook down on table)

40:17.416 --> 40:19.115
(sighing)

40:20.752 --> 40:21.818
- Hut!

40:21.820 --> 40:23.386
- Let's go! Let's hustle up.
Let's go.

40:23.388 --> 40:24.888
- Let's go! Let's go, go, go!

40:24.890 --> 40:25.955
- Get it back in!

40:25.957 --> 40:27.357
- PAULA: Rob, can we
just ask some questions?

40:27.359 --> 40:29.392
- KAMAL: Not right now,
Paula. We're busy.

40:29.394 --> 40:30.760
- You guys are
always busy for us.

40:30.762 --> 40:33.863
- ROB: What, what? C'mon, fast.
What's the question?

40:34.065 --> 40:36.299
- Rob, we just wanted to get
clarity on what you do

40:36.301 --> 40:37.700
with the gun crime?

40:37.702 --> 40:39.869
How you plan on keeping it
out of the city.

40:39.871 --> 40:42.372
- I don't know. That's what I'm
going to sit down

40:42.374 --> 40:44.274
with the Prime Minister
to find out.

40:44.276 --> 40:46.676
You know, about how our
immigration laws work.

40:46.678 --> 40:49.479
No, obviously, I have an idea,
but whatever I can do

40:49.481 --> 40:52.215
to get them out of this city,
I'm going to.

40:52.217 --> 40:53.850
- Thanks, Paula. Thanks.
- All right.

40:53.852 --> 40:57.053
- C'mon! Don't do the bullshit
Macarena for me, c'mon!

40:57.055 --> 40:58.755
Step it up, c'mon!

40:59.791 --> 41:01.257
- Set.

41:01.259 --> 41:02.759
Hut.

41:02.761 --> 41:05.795
- Hey, come on, Jack.
Let's go! Let's go!

41:11.136 --> 41:12.802
(sighs)

41:13.004 --> 41:14.337
- Any movement?

41:14.339 --> 41:16.739
- Um, not yet. I can't
get a hold of him yet.

41:16.741 --> 41:19.542
- You have anyone
else to speak to?

41:21.246 --> 41:22.946
Yeah!

41:24.149 --> 41:25.415
- Hey, David.

41:25.417 --> 41:27.250
- Uhh, yeah?

41:27.986 --> 41:29.919
- Uh, what would you do?

41:30.288 --> 41:31.688
- Uh, I'd have given this story

41:31.690 --> 41:34.057
to someone with a
little more experience.

41:34.059 --> 41:35.758
(scoffs)

41:37.429 --> 41:39.295
Uh, shit. I'm sorry.

41:39.297 --> 41:41.164
Look, um...

41:41.166 --> 41:42.966
Who else knows him?

41:42.968 --> 41:44.334
You're guy.

41:44.336 --> 41:46.035
- Right.
- Start there.

41:50.442 --> 41:52.141
- Okay.

41:56.815 --> 41:59.015
- Excuse me. Hey!
I was here last week

41:59.017 --> 42:02.018
on Wednesday. I don't know
if you were working, I...

42:02.020 --> 42:04.053
(gentle score begins)

42:05.090 --> 42:06.422
It's...

42:06.424 --> 42:08.124
Okay. All right.

42:18.069 --> 42:19.869
- Uh.

42:35.053 --> 42:36.586
- BRAM: Um, just a
couple of quick...

42:36.588 --> 42:37.954
<i> - WOMAN: Sorry.</i>
