57:13.898 --> 57:16.732
- Ah! You got the first job
you applied for out of the gate.

57:16.734 --> 57:17.666
- Internship.

57:17.668 --> 57:19.001
- They're paying you, now.

57:19.002 --> 57:20.335
But you are lucky that you
don't have to worry about money.

57:20.337 --> 57:21.403
We're lucky.

57:21.405 --> 57:22.838
- Yes, I know. I know that.

57:22.840 --> 57:24.873
But I can't feel frustrated
because everyone's

57:24.875 --> 57:26.208
knee-jerk reaction is
"You're so lucky.

57:26.210 --> 57:27.409
You don't have to
feel frustrated."

57:27.411 --> 57:28.811
- You know, at Versailles,

57:28.813 --> 57:30.546
Marie-Antoinette had this
peasant's village built,

57:30.548 --> 57:32.448
like a fake one.
She wanted to feel

57:32.450 --> 57:34.450
like she was doing something,
so she built this shack

57:34.452 --> 57:36.552
where she could milk cows
and, like, I don't know,

57:36.554 --> 57:38.053
tend to the earth.

57:38.055 --> 57:40.422
- Okay, honestly, I can't begin
to do the mental gymnastics

57:40.424 --> 57:42.458
to untangle that, but I'm just
very happy for you

57:42.460 --> 57:44.626
that you found a use
for your major in history.

57:44.628 --> 57:46.929
- It's sort of tough to complain
when you have an $800 machine

57:46.931 --> 57:48.931
in your hand that could land
Apollo 13.

57:48.933 --> 57:51.800
You are a young, well-off,
relatively intelligent,

57:51.802 --> 57:52.568
white male.

57:52.570 --> 57:53.669
- Marie-Antoinette was beheaded

57:53.671 --> 57:55.003
along with her
white, male husband.

57:55.005 --> 57:57.739
- What could you possibly
feel disaffected about?

57:57.741 --> 57:59.241
- Maybe the fact that
I'm supposed to be

57:59.243 --> 58:02.110
super-content and happy and
everything's supposed to come

58:02.112 --> 58:03.846
very easily to me, so

58:03.848 --> 58:06.048
whenever I find myself having
moments of perfectly normal

58:06.050 --> 58:08.750
human sadness, or fear,

58:08.752 --> 58:09.985
or doubt,

58:09.987 --> 58:11.753
nobody takes it seriously.

58:11.755 --> 58:13.522
And Apollo 13 didn't land.

58:13.524 --> 58:15.224
- Well, that's 'cause
they didn't have the phone.

58:15.226 --> 58:17.526
- That's because no one checked
to make sure that the people

58:17.528 --> 58:18.861
they were sending into nowhere

58:18.863 --> 58:20.529
were in a vehicle that wouldn't
blow up in their faces.

58:20.531 --> 58:22.397
They just trusted that
the shuttle they were in

58:22.399 --> 58:23.699
point A to point B

58:23.701 --> 58:25.634
because that's what
they were told.

58:26.136 --> 58:29.605
- Listen! I-I tried. I tried
to figure something out.

58:31.141 --> 58:32.841
Hold on.

58:33.744 --> 58:35.777
If you come out with this...

58:35.779 --> 58:37.279
Hello?

58:40.217 --> 58:41.917
(tense score begins)

1:00:09.173 --> 1:00:10.872
(text arriving ding)

1:00:11.442 --> 1:00:13.141
(typewriter keys clacking)

1:00:16.447 --> 1:00:18.146
(message arriving whoop)

1:00:20.284 --> 1:00:21.984
(message sending swoop)

1:00:30.861 --> 1:00:32.761
(typewriter keys clacking)

1:00:35.065 --> 1:00:36.965
(typewriter keys clacking
very quickly)

1:00:52.416 --> 1:00:54.116
(typewriter keys clacking)

1:01:10.167 --> 1:01:11.867
(car engine rumbling)

1:01:15.773 --> 1:01:18.740
- Hey, did I tell you I ran into
Becky Blidner on the subway?

1:01:18.742 --> 1:01:21.243
She was wearing a suit.
Where are we?

1:01:21.245 --> 1:01:23.311
- She's probably miserable
and going home.

1:01:23.313 --> 1:01:26.048
- Well, no, it was the morning.
How long are you gonna be?

1:01:26.050 --> 1:01:27.949
- She's probably miserable
and going to work.

1:01:27.951 --> 1:01:29.851
- I was coming back
from an interview.

1:01:29.853 --> 1:01:31.787
We're supposed
to meet them by 11.

1:01:31.789 --> 1:01:33.388
- Yeah, we'll get there.

1:01:33.390 --> 1:01:35.123
- On Bram time.

1:01:35.392 --> 1:01:37.192
Google's opening an office here.

1:01:37.194 --> 1:01:38.593
- Ah, here.

1:01:38.595 --> 1:01:40.295
- Where?

1:01:43.000 --> 1:01:44.933
- I blew it, anyway.
They ask you all these questions

1:01:44.935 --> 1:01:46.868
that nobody can answer,
by the way, like,

1:01:46.870 --> 1:01:48.870
how many times in a day
does a clock's hands overlap?

1:01:48.872 --> 1:01:50.839
- How much do you
think this house cost?

1:01:50.841 --> 1:01:53.408
- I don't know.
It was 22, somehow.

1:01:53.410 --> 1:01:56.945
- He paid just under 300
for it, like, ten years ago.

1:01:56.947 --> 1:01:58.180
- Who?

1:01:58.182 --> 1:02:01.049
- Rob. If you bought it now
it'd cost, like, $900,000.

1:02:01.051 --> 1:02:04.286
- Okay, Bram, are you fucked?
What are we even doing here?

1:02:04.288 --> 1:02:05.487
- The guy's not answering me.

1:02:05.489 --> 1:02:08.690
- He's not answering you?
I wonder what that's like?

1:02:08.692 --> 1:02:09.958
We should go.

1:02:09.960 --> 1:02:11.493
- Look, if he's not real,
then I'm updating Twitter

1:02:11.495 --> 1:02:13.195
with links to some intern's
lists until they realize

1:02:13.197 --> 1:02:14.996
that interns can write lists
and tweet.

1:02:14.998 --> 1:02:16.832
- Maybe it's better
if he's not real.

1:02:16.834 --> 1:02:18.667
- You know how much
his father was worth?

1:02:18.669 --> 1:02:19.968
- Honestly, I don't care.

1:02:19.970 --> 1:02:21.636
- Everything he has
he can thank his dad for.

1:02:21.638 --> 1:02:23.705
- As we sit in your dad's Benz.

1:02:23.707 --> 1:02:25.107
Let's go, seriously.

1:02:25.109 --> 1:02:26.775
- Wait, why do you
think it's not real?

1:02:26.777 --> 1:02:28.009
- I said that it might not be,

1:02:28.011 --> 1:02:29.211
it's probably better
if it's not.

1:02:29.213 --> 1:02:30.712
- The guy's the mayor
and he's on camera

1:02:30.714 --> 1:02:32.347
smoking crack in a crack den.

1:02:32.349 --> 1:02:33.515
- Allegedly.

1:02:33.684 --> 1:02:35.050
- Allegedly.

1:02:35.052 --> 1:02:36.485
I wouldn't even know
where to find crack,

1:02:36.487 --> 1:02:37.819
let alone a den full of it.

1:02:37.821 --> 1:02:39.421
- Well, maybe you should start
by asking the guy

1:02:39.423 --> 1:02:40.622
that deals you weed.

1:02:40.624 --> 1:02:41.823
- Oh, yeah, I'm sure that
Noah Schwartz

1:02:41.825 --> 1:02:43.258
of Congregation
Sheket Bevakasha--

1:02:43.260 --> 1:02:44.860
- Hey!

1:02:44.862 --> 1:02:48.296
- ...knows all the finest crack
and opium dens in Forest Hill.

1:02:48.298 --> 1:02:50.232
- I wish opium dens
were still a thing.

1:02:50.234 --> 1:02:51.733
- And-and that's
not the same thing.

1:02:51.735 --> 1:02:52.801
- Oh, yeah, no.

1:02:52.803 --> 1:02:55.504
Crack is whack,
opium is dope-ium.

1:02:55.939 --> 1:02:58.173
- I met the guy. He's real.

1:02:58.175 --> 1:03:00.008
- You know, isn't there
this whole subset of journalism

1:03:00.010 --> 1:03:02.778
where you get to make up
wildly inaccurate shit,

1:03:02.780 --> 1:03:04.813
tweet it to the masses
and still get some of your own

1:03:04.815 --> 1:03:06.248
press while doing so?

1:03:06.250 --> 1:03:09.684
That way, it's sort of worth it
when they expose you.

1:03:09.686 --> 1:03:11.153
- How is that worth it?

1:03:11.155 --> 1:03:12.888
- You get your
own Wikipedia page.

1:03:12.890 --> 1:03:14.923
(bang on window!)

1:03:16.126 --> 1:03:17.959
- What did you think you were
going to find sitting outside

1:03:17.961 --> 1:03:19.361
of his house? I'm just curious.

1:03:19.363 --> 1:03:22.030
- If he-if he left I could see
where he went for myself

1:03:22.032 --> 1:03:25.467
and not just from other people
on Instagram the next day.

1:03:25.469 --> 1:03:26.768
(chuckles)

1:03:26.770 --> 1:03:28.470
- You told the cops you were
working on a story

1:03:28.472 --> 1:03:30.305
for the paper, is that right?

1:03:30.307 --> 1:03:32.007
- I am!

1:03:33.577 --> 1:03:35.076
- I don't know if I didn't
make myself clear

1:03:35.078 --> 1:03:36.745
or if you have a drug problem
I'm not aware of--

1:03:36.747 --> 1:03:38.713
- Yes! Yes, I fucked up. I know.

1:03:38.715 --> 1:03:40.715
- Well, I'm glad
that got through.

1:03:40.717 --> 1:03:43.652
Look at me: you do not
pitch stories!

1:03:43.654 --> 1:03:45.053
You are assigned things!

1:03:45.055 --> 1:03:47.355
You do not use the paper's name
when you are caught

1:03:47.357 --> 1:03:50.158
staking out the mayor's house.
You get it?

1:03:50.594 --> 1:03:52.294
- I'm sorry.

1:03:59.169 --> 1:04:00.836
- You know, I actually wish we
were paying you more,

1:04:00.838 --> 1:04:02.470
I really do.

1:04:02.472 --> 1:04:05.941
That way we could just
cut you from the budget.

1:04:07.077 --> 1:04:10.111
It's funny how when you're
dispensable you're actually not.

1:04:26.430 --> 1:04:28.129
(phone ringing)

1:04:28.398 --> 1:04:30.098
- This is Ashley.

1:04:30.634 --> 1:04:32.334
Hi.

1:04:35.205 --> 1:04:36.905
A-about what?

1:04:40.377 --> 1:04:41.643
(scoffs)

1:04:41.645 --> 1:04:43.345
What?

1:04:44.948 --> 1:04:46.648
(score begins)

1:04:47.117 --> 1:04:48.683
I'll have to call you
back on that.

1:04:57.294 --> 1:04:58.727
- What?

1:04:58.729 --> 1:05:00.428
(cell phone buzzes)

1:05:08.839 --> 1:05:11.673
- Hey! I didn't know
what happened to you.

1:05:12.009 --> 1:05:14.109
Well, that's hard to say
without seeing, uh,

1:05:14.111 --> 1:05:17.145
what we're paying for.
How much were you thinking?

1:05:17.381 --> 1:05:18.446
Well...

1:05:18.448 --> 1:05:20.415
Well, they won't go above
your asking price,

1:05:20.417 --> 1:05:23.451
so you should definitely
start higher than you want.

1:05:26.757 --> 1:05:28.456
300,000.

1:05:28.759 --> 1:05:30.759
- I hope we're
discussing lira.

1:05:30.761 --> 1:05:31.860
- Does anyone still use lira?

1:05:31.862 --> 1:05:32.727
- Lebanon.

1:05:32.729 --> 1:05:33.662
- No, they have the pound.

1:05:33.664 --> 1:05:34.763
- Well, they
call it a lira.

1:05:34.765 --> 1:05:36.031
- Turkey has the lira. Stop.

1:05:36.033 --> 1:05:38.233
We're not paying 300,000
anything for a video.

1:05:38.235 --> 1:05:40.602
- Well, he started with 150.

1:05:40.604 --> 1:05:42.570
- You negotiated up?

1:05:43.006 --> 1:05:46.041
- No, no. Um, he said that
they wouldn't go below 150

1:05:46.043 --> 1:05:47.709
and so I said that
he should start higher

1:05:47.711 --> 1:05:49.744
so there's room to negotiate.

1:05:49.746 --> 1:05:51.546
- So you negotiated up.

1:05:51.548 --> 1:05:54.182
- If the Globe knows,
all the papers know.

1:05:54.184 --> 1:05:55.417
One of them is gonna get it.

1:05:55.419 --> 1:05:56.918
- Did they say how much
the guy was asking?

1:05:56.920 --> 1:05:58.520
We could offer them more.

1:05:58.522 --> 1:06:00.221
- Offer them more?

1:06:00.590 --> 1:06:02.057
- Let's offer
them ten grand.

1:06:02.059 --> 1:06:04.526
- For what? We haven't seen
what we're even discussing.

1:06:04.528 --> 1:06:06.861
If we're taking some guy
who disappeared for two weeks--

1:06:06.863 --> 1:06:08.563
- Three.

1:06:09.566 --> 1:06:11.533
- Three weeks!

1:06:11.535 --> 1:06:13.535
You're good. We're taking
some guy who disappeared

1:06:13.537 --> 1:06:15.937
for three weeks' word
that there is a video

1:06:15.939 --> 1:06:18.673
that someone may
want to see, maybe...

1:06:18.675 --> 1:06:19.975
Where are you supposed
to meet him?

1:06:19.977 --> 1:06:22.043
- We're not telling
anyone anything.

1:06:22.045 --> 1:06:24.179
- I was just asking if--

1:06:25.115 --> 1:06:27.649
I want to make sure it doesn't
look like we were lying

1:06:27.651 --> 1:06:29.250
when this eventually leaks.

1:06:29.252 --> 1:06:31.619
- You know what happens if this
leaks? He loses his job.

1:06:31.621 --> 1:06:34.055
And you know what happens
when he loses his?

1:06:34.057 --> 1:06:35.757
- If it leaks?

1:06:35.759 --> 1:06:36.825
- So, what's in the budget?

1:06:36.827 --> 1:06:38.860
- TMZ pays money
for these stories.

1:06:38.862 --> 1:06:40.528
- TMZ also has revenue.

1:06:40.530 --> 1:06:41.997
- We are a real newspaper

1:06:41.999 --> 1:06:43.531
and we have a responsibility
as journalists

1:06:43.533 --> 1:06:46.134
- We have a responsibility to
the city and, more importantly,

1:06:46.136 --> 1:06:48.236
to the people looking at your
bottom line every day

1:06:48.238 --> 1:06:51.239
where your salary is one of the
very brightest red numbers.

1:06:51.241 --> 1:06:53.775
Do you know what kind of traffic
this can pull to the site?

1:06:53.777 --> 1:06:54.976
- We are a newspaper!

1:06:54.978 --> 1:06:57.579
- We don't deal in news
anymore, Judith.

1:07:01.051 --> 1:07:02.751
(phone ringing)

1:07:05.956 --> 1:07:07.655
(phone ringing)

1:07:18.735 --> 1:07:20.835
- Oh, it's-it's just a
statement.

1:07:20.837 --> 1:07:22.904
Some questions...

1:07:22.906 --> 1:07:24.873
- I still work for the city.

1:07:24.875 --> 1:07:27.409
- I-I get it. We also do.

1:07:27.411 --> 1:07:30.478
We have the same boss,
technically, me and you.

1:07:30.480 --> 1:07:33.214
- Even if we were
to pay them something...

1:07:33.216 --> 1:07:35.917
we just fired people
to save money.

1:07:35.919 --> 1:07:38.586
We are not looking
to add expenses here.

1:07:38.588 --> 1:07:41.056
And they're looking
for a ridiculous amount.

1:07:41.058 --> 1:07:43.658
- But what if we, uh,
partnered with someone

1:07:43.660 --> 1:07:45.260
like they did on WikiLeaks?

1:07:45.262 --> 1:07:46.928
- I don't think The Times
or Der Spiegel would have

1:07:46.930 --> 1:07:49.397
the same level of interest they
had in the US State Department

1:07:49.399 --> 1:07:52.467
spying on the UN that they would
in a Canadian mayor

1:07:52.469 --> 1:07:53.635
smoking crack.

1:07:53.637 --> 1:07:55.837
And they didn't pay.

1:07:55.839 --> 1:07:57.405
- No, but I know
they got approached.

1:07:57.407 --> 1:07:58.907
The Star, probably
The Globe, too.

1:07:58.909 --> 1:08:00.075
- What?

1:08:00.077 --> 1:08:01.676
- Bram's guy spoke to them--
The Star.

1:08:01.678 --> 1:08:02.744
- How do you know that?

1:08:05.348 --> 1:08:08.683
- I know someone over there
that can't really keep a secret.

1:08:08.685 --> 1:08:10.285
- You think they're having the
same conversation

1:08:10.287 --> 1:08:12.654
about you at The Star right now?

1:08:15.192 --> 1:08:17.258
- Come here a second?

1:08:17.260 --> 1:08:19.861
- We can work it
around your schedule.

1:08:20.664 --> 1:08:22.597
- I have to think about it.

1:08:23.667 --> 1:08:25.800
- Well, what if we get Ashley,
that girl from his office?

1:08:25.802 --> 1:08:26.734
She wouldn't go on record,

1:08:26.736 --> 1:08:28.103
but what if we did
get her on record?

1:08:28.105 --> 1:08:29.504
- Nobody gives a fuck
about her story!

1:08:29.506 --> 1:08:33.241
They want to see a video
of a mayor smoking crack.

1:08:35.679 --> 1:08:37.045
- Yo.

1:08:37.047 --> 1:08:39.147
- Remember the budget increase
we voted against?

1:08:39.149 --> 1:08:40.115
Office expenses?

1:08:40.117 --> 1:08:41.516
- "Office expenses". Yeah.

1:08:41.518 --> 1:08:43.518
- It was voted through, but Rob
refused to take it.

1:08:43.520 --> 1:08:45.887
Where does it live?
The refused amount.

1:08:45.889 --> 1:08:47.422
- Technically?

1:08:47.424 --> 1:08:49.691
I guess it's in our
office purses

1:08:49.693 --> 1:08:51.726
and whatever surplus is left
at the end of fiscal

1:08:51.728 --> 1:08:53.128
goes back into the pot.

1:08:53.130 --> 1:08:56.131
- And they, uh, argued that
office means "office".

1:08:56.133 --> 1:08:57.765
Like, in the end,
they're using it for what?

1:08:57.767 --> 1:09:01.069
- Whatever. Dubman uses it
to sponsor a little league team.

1:09:01.071 --> 1:09:02.537
- You can use it
in your community?

1:09:02.539 --> 1:09:04.339
- You can. Why?

1:09:04.341 --> 1:09:06.541
- I wanna give to a community
charity using "office" expenses.

1:09:06.543 --> 1:09:07.709
Kosher?

1:09:07.711 --> 1:09:09.310
- Dubman and Inchens and them
do a "women's lunch"

1:09:09.312 --> 1:09:10.812
for themselves once in a while.

1:09:10.814 --> 1:09:12.780
It's charged to their offices,
so if the people of Toronto

1:09:12.782 --> 1:09:15.350
are unknowingly paying for
$20 kale Caesars,

1:09:15.352 --> 1:09:16.751
I'm sure they'll be fine
not knowing they're also

1:09:16.753 --> 1:09:17.585
giving to charity.

1:09:17.587 --> 1:09:18.319
- Great.

1:09:22.726 --> 1:09:24.092
- I want to know
what is on there,

1:09:24.094 --> 1:09:25.827
so make sure he thinks
we have more than we do.

1:09:30.267 --> 1:09:33.001
- This is good, Judith.

1:09:33.003 --> 1:09:34.068
You can smile.

1:09:34.871 --> 1:09:36.804
- Go back to your desk.

1:09:40.477 --> 1:09:42.177
(door closes)

1:09:54.624 --> 1:09:56.324
(paper tearing)

1:10:24.254 --> 1:10:25.954
(van side door slides shut)

1:11:11.268 --> 1:11:12.834
(van door closes)

1:11:12.836 --> 1:11:14.769
- What's good?

1:11:25.482 --> 1:11:27.615
- Should I put these on?

1:11:28.051 --> 1:11:30.418
- I mean, if you wanna listen.

1:12:46.396 --> 1:12:48.096
- All right, man.

1:12:49.065 --> 1:12:50.765
That's enough.

1:12:51.368 --> 1:12:53.134
- Can I watch it again?

1:12:53.136 --> 1:12:54.836
- Nah.

1:12:54.838 --> 1:12:56.537
Just one for free, man.

1:12:57.073 --> 1:12:58.573
- Were you there?

1:12:58.575 --> 1:13:00.041
(scoffs)

1:13:00.043 --> 1:13:01.642
- Yes.

1:13:01.644 --> 1:13:03.778
- Did you take the video?

1:13:06.049 --> 1:13:07.749
- He was there.

1:13:09.919 --> 1:13:11.619
- What's in the pipe?

1:13:13.022 --> 1:13:14.555
- Wha... Whadda you think, hm?

1:13:14.557 --> 1:13:16.724
- I'm just-I'm just makin' sure.

1:13:16.726 --> 1:13:21.396
- So, what are you maybe
thinking about the money?

1:13:22.699 --> 1:13:24.766
- I think we can
get you some.

1:13:24.768 --> 1:13:28.002
- Okay, so why don't you
tell your boss what you saw

1:13:28.004 --> 1:13:30.104
and, uh, tell me a number, hm?

1:13:38.815 --> 1:13:40.515
- Okay.

